#Text=THE DORSET COUNTY CHRONICLE AND SOMERSETSHIRE GAZETTE
#Text=THE CHURCH
#Text=Cambridge, Dec. 19.
#Text=—At a congregation on Tuesday last, a letter trom the Marquis Camden, accepting the high honor conferre i upon him, «as read to the Senate.
#Text=The Noble Marquis, after expressing, in feeling terms, his regret for the death of the late Chancellor, his H.

#Text=H. the Duke of Gloucester, stated he could not adequately convey the sense he entertained of the high honor conferred upon him in selecting him for the important office of Chancellor, at a time when attempts were making not only to subvert the discipline and management of the Established Church, but its very existence, and of our most venerated institutions.

#Text=His Lordship further said, it would be his most anxious endeavour to promote the interests of the University, and maintain the connexion of Church and State, and hoped for the assistance of that distinguished body to which be was united.

#Text=He concluded by again expressing bis acknowledgments for the good opinion personally entertained of him by the University, which he would endeavour to show was not misplaced ; and the distinguished honor he felt at being placed at the head of that body which, throughout his life, he so much venerated
#Text=At a congregation on Wednesday, his Grace the Duke of Northumberland was appointed High Steward of this University, in the place of the Right Honourable the Earl of Hardwicke, deceased.
#Text=At the same congregation, Mr.
#Text=Christopher Wordsworth, of Trinity College, and Mr.
#Text=Lofft, of King’s College, were appointed Examiners for the Pitt scholars.
#Text=The vicarage of Battersea, we understand, was given by Lord Melbourne to the Kev.
#Text=Mr.
#Text=Eden, a relative of Lord Auckland’s.
#Text=New Churches.

#Text=—The cause of Episcopal religion seems to be spreading a.pace in the north of England, and we trust it ever will maintain a glorious ascendancy : thanks to its worthy and indefatigable ministers.
#Text=One new Church has lately been opened at South Shields, another just finished at Stocktou, and another is in progress at North Shields.
#Text=The foundation stone of one was laid at Stockton about a fortnight since, and another will be commenced at Darlington immediately after Christmas.
#Text=The whole of these Churches are, we believe, in the early English style of Gothic Architecture.
